    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-29T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-29T15:00:00-05:00" n="420"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d420">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">660C.116/199: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Poland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cudahy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-29T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 29, 1936—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Embassy’s No. 141, December 3, 5 p.m. Department desires you to seek an early
                    interview with the Minister for Foreign Affairs and <pb facs="0557" n="546"
                        xml:id="pg_546"/> to take up with him the application of the direct shipment
                    requirement to commodities of American origin, with particular reference to raw
                    cotton.</p>
                <p>You should state that your Government considers the application of this
                    requirement to be in direct violation of the ninth paragraph of Article 6 of the
                    treaty of June 15, 1931, with Poland (which you should cite), and that in view
                    of the unambiguous language of the treaty it is at a loss to understand the
                    action of the Polish Government in imposing the direct shipment requirement upon
                    articles of American origin. You should say that your Government expects that
                    the Polish Government will promptly take steps to accord to merchandise of
                    American origin which enters Poland by an indirect route the treatment to which
                    it is entitled under the provisions of the treaty.</p>
                <p>Please report briefly by cable and fully by despatch the result of your
                    representations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
